{"title_page": "Houston riot of 1917", "text_new": "{{Infobox civil conflict\n| image = [[File:Largest Murder Trial in the History of the United States. Scene during Court Martial of 64 members . . . - NARA - 533485.tif|300px]]\n| place = [[Houston, Texas]]\n| date = \n| caption = Court Martial of 64 members of the 24th Infantry. Trial started November 1, 1917, [[Fort Sam Houston]]\n| map_type = \n| map_caption = \n| map_size = \n| goals   = \n| side1= [[24th Infantry Regiment (United States)|Twenty-fourth United States Infantry Regiment]] soldiers\n| side2= [[Houston Police Department|Houston police]]\n| leadfigures1= Regiment commander\n| leadfigures2= [[General John Wilson Ruckman]];<br /> Sheriff John Tobin;<br /> [[Woodrow Wilson]] \n| casualties1= '''Deaths''': 20 (19 executed after court-martials and other proceedings; 1 suicide)<br />'''Injuries''': <br />'''Arrests''': 51+\n| casualties2= '''Deaths''': 16 (11 civilians and five policemen; 4 soldiers killed by friendly fire)<br />unknown number of wounded\n| casualties_label= Arrests, etc\n}}\nThe '''Camp Logan Mutiny''' (also called the '''Houston Riot of 1917''') was a reaction by 156 soldiers of the Third Battalion of the all-black [[24th Infantry Regiment (United States)|Twenty-fourth United States Infantry Regiment]] after members of the [[Houston Police Department]] harassed members of the local black community and the black soldiers who attempted to intervene were also violently accosted.  It took place over a single night, and resulted in the deaths of 11 civilians, five policemen, and four soldiers. The soldiers were tried at three [[courts-martial]] for [[mutiny]]. Nineteen were executed, and 41 were sentenced to life imprisonment.\n\nGregg Andrews, author of ''Thyra J. Edwards: Black Activist in the Global Freedom Struggle'', wrote that the event \"shook race relations in the city and created conditions that helped to spark a statewide surge of wartime racial activism\".<ref>Andrews, Gregg. ''Thyra J. Edwards: Black Activist in the Global Freedom Struggle''. [[University of Missouri Press]], 2011/06/14. {{ISBN|0826219128}}, 9780826219121. p. [https://archive.org/details/thyrajedwardsbla00andr/page/20 20].</ref>\n\n==Preliminary situation==\n[[File:003 Map of Buffalo Bayou area - Camp Logan Riots.jpg|thumb|left|Map of Buffalo Bayou area \u2013 Camp Logan Riots (circa 1917)]]\nShortly after the United States declared war on the [[Imperial Germany|German Empire]] in the spring of 1917, the War Department rushed to construct two new military installations in [[Harris County, Texas]] \u2014 [[Camp Logan]] and [[Ellington Field]].<ref name=\"eric.ed.gov\">{{Citation|last=Johnson|first=Thomas A.|title=A History of the Houston Police Department|accessdate=2013-03-02|year=1999|url=http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/detail?accno=ED446013}}</ref> On July 27, 1917, the Army ordered the Third Battalion of the Twenty-fourth United States Infantry Regiment to Houston to guard the Camp Logan construction site. The regiment traveled to Houston by train from their camp at [[Columbus, New Mexico]], accompanied by seven commissioned officers.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n== Precipitating causes==\nAlmost from the arrival of the Twenty-fourth Infantry in Houston, the presence of black soldiers in the segregated Texas city caused conflict.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\">{{cite court |litigants=United States vs. Sergeant William C. Nesbit, et al.|vol=vol 1|url=http://cdm16035.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p15568coll1/id/2058/rec/7 }}</ref>{{rp|10}} The [[Jim Crow laws]] had not been enforced when the Twenty-fourth was deployed in [[Columbus, New Mexico]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Negro Uprising Been Feared For Days, Says Chief|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=August 24, 1917|page=5}}</ref> but in Houston the soldiers encountered segregated street cars and white workers at Camp Logan who demanded separate tanks of drinking water. Soldiers from the Twenty-fourth were involved in a number of \"clashes\" with city police, several of which resulted in the soldiers receiving minor injuries.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|10}}\n\nAround noon August 23, 1917, Lee Sparks and Rufus Daniels, two [[Houston]] police officers, broke up a craps game on a street corner in Houston's predominantly-black San Felipe district by firing warning shots.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|12}} Sparks, searching for the fleeing suspects, entered the house of local resident Sara Travers.<ref name=\"HoustonMutiny\">{{cite journal|title=The Houston Mutiny of 1917|journal=Trotter Review|date=January 1, 2009|last=Christian|first=Garna L.|volume=18|issue=1|page=112|url=http://scholarworks.umb.edu/trotter_review/vol18/iss1/14}}</ref> He did not find the suspect but, after exchanging words with Travers, struck her and dragged her outside in her nightgown.<ref name=\"crisis.nov.1917\">{{Cite news|issn=0011-1422|volume=15|issue=1|pages=14\u201319|last=Greuning|first=Martha|title=Houston: An N.A.A.C.P. Investigation|work=[[The Crisis]]|date=November 1917|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O1oEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14}}</ref>\n\nAs Sparks and Daniels called in the arrest from an area patrol box, they were approached by Private Alonzo Edwards. Edwards offered to take custody of Travers, but was pistol-whipped repeatedly by Sparks and then arrested.<ref name=\"crisis.nov.1917\"/> Later that afternoon, Corporal Charles Baltimore approached Sparks and Daniels in the same neighborhood to inquire about the status of Edwards. Sparks struck Baltimore with his pistol and fired three shots at him as he fled into a nearby home. Sparks and Daniels pursued Baltimore, eventually finding him under a bed. They pulled him out, beat him, and placed him under arrest.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|10}}\n\nA rumor reached the camp of the Twenty-fourth that Baltimore had been shot and killed. The soldiers immediately began meeting in small groups to discuss plans to march on Houston and attack the police.<ref name=\"Tillman\">{{cite court|litigants=United States vs. Corporal Robert Tillman, et al., 24th Infantry|vol=vol 2|url=http://cdm16035.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p15568coll1/id/2068/rec/6}}</ref>{{rp|1390}} An officer from the Twenty-fourth retrieved the injured Baltimore from the police station, which seemed to calm the soldiers for the moment.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|126}}\n\n==The mutiny==\nThe officers of the Twenty-fourth continued to receive reports of impending trouble from the angry soldiers.<ref name=\"Washington\">{{cite court|litigants=Record of Trial by General Court Martial of Corporal John Washington, et al., 24th Infantry|vol=vol 1|pinpoint=p. 22|url=http://cdm16035.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p15568coll1/id/2055/rec/7}}</ref> Major K.S. Snow revoked all passes for the evening and ordered the guard to be increased, but later that evening stumbled upon a group of men stealing ammunition from one of the supply tents.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|39}} He ordered the men to assemble without arms and warned them that it was \"utterly foolish, foolhardy, for them to think of taking the law into their own hands.\"<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|40}} One of the men, who had smuggled his rifle into the formation, fired it and cried out that a mob was approaching the camp. At this point, order broke down completely and the soldiers mobbed the supply tents, grabbing rifles and ammunition.<ref name=\"Tillman\"/>{{rp|1292}}\n\nThe soldiers began firing indiscriminately into the surrounding buildings. After several minutes of shooting, Sergeant Vida Henry ordered the men in the area \u2013 about 150 \u2013 to fill their canteens, grab extra ammunition, and fall in to march on Houston.<ref name=\"Tillman\"/>{{rp|1295}} The group marched through neighborhoods on the outskirts of the city, firing at houses with outdoor lights. They fired on a car with two white occupants, but let a second car with black occupants leave unharmed.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|1214}} They marched nearly two and a half miles, all the way to the San Felipe district, before they encountered any police officers. Due to the disorganization of the police department, officers had only been sent out in small numbers<ref name=\"Haynes\"/>{{rp|141}} so the first police casualties occurred when a group of six officers stumbled upon the entire column of soldiers. Two policemen (including Rufus Daniels) were killed immediately, and one later died of wounds he had sustained.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|527}}\n\nThe soldiers stopped a car carrying two policemen, who were disarmed and shot. \nA few blocks later, an open-topped car carrying a man in an olive-drab uniform approached the column. Believing this to be the uniform of a Houston mounted policeman, the soldiers opened fire only to discover later that they had killed Captain Joseph W. Mattes of the Illinois National Guard.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|651}} The killing of a military officer drove home the seriousness of their actions and the pending consequences.<ref name=\"Haynes\"/>{{rp|162}}\nMattes' body was found mutilated to the point of being nearly unrecognizable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZHIaAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA577&lpg=PA577&dq=Captain+Joseph+W.+Mattes+of#v=onepage|title=The Chicago Daily News Almanac and Year-Book|date=13 April 2019|publisher=Chicago Daily News Company|via=Google Books}}</ref>\nMany soldiers began to desert the group, and Sergeant Henry led the remainder on a march to return to camp. Just outside the San Felipe district, Henry shook hands with the remaining soldiers and informed them that he planned to kill himself after they left.<ref name=\"Tillman\"/>{{rp|1322}} Henry's body was found in the area the next day, with a crushed skull and bayonet wound to the shoulder..<ref name=\"henryinquest\">{{Cite web|url=http://cdm16035.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15568coll1/id/2145/rec/2|title=Vida Henry Inquest|date=August 24, 1917}}</ref>\n\nBy the time the shooting had stopped, 17 people were dead (four police officers, nine civilians, and two soldiers).<ref name=\"listofdead\">{{cite news|title=17 Killed; 21 Are Injured in Wild Night|work=Houston Chronicle|date=August 24, 1917|page=1}}</ref> One soldier and a police officer later died from wounds sustained during the riot, and one soldier died from wounds sustained during his capture the next day. All of the wounds received by soldiers the night of the riot were the result of [[friendly fire|accidental shootings by fellow soldiers]].<ref name=\"Haynes\"/>{{rp|169}}\n\n==Immediate aftermath==\nThe next morning, Houston was placed under martial law.<ref name=\"martiallaw\">{{cite news|title=Martial Law Declared |work=[[Houston Post]]|date=August 24, 1917|page=1}}</ref> The remaining soldiers in the Twenty-fourth's camp were disarmed, and a house-to-house search discovered a number of soldiers hiding in the San Felipe district. Soldiers in local jails were turned over to the Army, and the Third Battalion was sent by rail back to New Mexico.<ref name=\"Trotter, Joe W 2001\">{{Cite book|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Company|last=Trotter|first=Joe William|title=The African American Experience: From Reconstruction|location=Boston|year=2001}}</ref>\n\nIn the ensuing [[court-martial]], almost two hundred witnesses testified over twenty-two days, and the transcripts of the testimony covered more than two thousand pages. Author Robert V. Haynes suggests that [[General John Wilson Ruckman]] was \"especially anxious for the courts-martial to begin\".<ref name=\"Haynes\">{{cite book|last=Haynes|first=Robert V.|title=A Night of Violence: The Houston Riot of 1917|url=https://archive.org/details/nightofviolencet00hayn|url-access=registration|year=1976|publisher=Louisiana State University Press|isbn=978-0-8071-0172-8}}</ref>{{rp|251}}\n\nRuckman had preferred the proceedings take place in [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]], but eventually agreed to allow them to remain in [[San Antonio]]. Haynes posits the decision was made to accommodate the witnesses who lived in Houston, plus \"the countless spectators\" who wanted to follow the proceedings (p.&nbsp;254).<ref name=\"Haynes\"/> Ruckman \"urged\" the War Department to select a \"prestigious court\".<ref name=\"Haynes\"/>{{rp|255}} Three brigadier generals were chosen, along with seven full colonels and three lieutenant colonels. Eight members of the court were [[West Point]] graduates. The court contained a geographic balance between northerners, southerners and westerners.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n[[File:002 Map 24th infantry camp; Houston, Texas, showing bullet holes in vicinity.jpg|thumb|left|Map 24th infantry camp; Houston, Texas, showing bullet holes in vicinity (circa 1917)]]\nThe Departmental Judge Advocate General, Colonel George Dunn, reviewed the record of the first court martial (known as \"the Nesbit Case.\") and approved the sentences. He forwarded the documents materials to Gen. Ruckman on December 3. Six days later, thirteen of the prisoners (including Corporal Baltimore) were told that they would be hanged for murder, but they were not informed of the time or place.<ref name=\"Haynes\"/>{{rp|3}} The court recommended clemency for a Private Hudson, but General Ruckman declined to grant it.\n\nThough 169 witnesses testified for the prosecution during the 22-day court-martial, many could not identify the defendants because the riots unfolded at night during heavy rain. Historians have also questioned the veracity of witness testimony, noting that the soldiers who testified as participants were granted immunity or promised leniency.<ref name=\"WaPo_082417\">{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Deneen L.|title=Relatives seek justice for the mass hanging of black soldiers after the bloody 1917 Houston riots|url=https://www.stripes.com/relatives-seek-justice-for-the-mass-hanging-of-black-soldiers-after-the-bloody-1917-houston-riots-1.484277|accessdate=February 12, 2018|agency=[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=August 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"smith1991\"/>\n\n==The first hanging==\nThe condemned soldiers (one sergeant, four corporals, and eight privates) were transferred to a barracks on December 10. That evening, motor trucks carried new lumber for scaffolds to some bathhouses built for the soldiers at Camp Travis near a swimming pool in the [[Salado Creek]]. The designated place of execution was several hundred yards away. Army engineers completed their work by the light of bonfires. The thirteen condemned men were awakened at five in the morning and taken to the gallows. They were hanged simultaneously, at 7:17am, one minute before sunrise. The scaffolds were disassembled and every piece returned to [[Fort Sam Houston]]. The ''[[New York Times]]'', commenting on the clean-up operations, observed the place of execution and place of burial were \"indistinguishable.\" Only army officers and County Sheriff John Tobin had been allowed to witness the execution.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nGen. Ruckman told reporters he had personally approved the death sentences and said that forty-one soldiers had been given life sentences and four received sentences of two and a half years or less. He said he was the one who chose the time and place for the executions.<ref name=\"Haynes\"/>{{rp|7}} Military jurist [[Frederick Bernays Wiener]] has observed that Ruckman's approval and execution of the death sentences were \"entirely legal\" and \"in complete conformity\" with the 1916 Articles of War.<ref name=Wiener/>{{rp|122}}\n\n==Second and third courts martial==\nA second court-martial, the \"Washington\" case, began six days later. Fifteen men of the Lower A Division were tried and five were sentenced to death. On January 2, 1918, Ruckman approved the sentences in a public statement. But a new rule, General Orders 167 (December 29, 1917), prohibited the execution of any death sentence until the [[Judge Advocate General]] (JAG) could review the sentence(s).<ref name=Wiener>{{cite journal|last1=Wiener|first1=Frederick Bernays|title=The Seamy Side of the World War I Court-Martial Controversy|journal=Military Law Review|date=1989|volume=123|pages=109\u201328|accessdate=December 11, 2015|url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/frd/Military_Law/Military_Law_Review/pdf-files/27607D~1.pdf#page=113}}</ref>{{rp|115}} (The JAG Boards of Review tasked with reviewing death sentences were created by a subsequent rule, General Orders 7 (January 7, 1918).<ref name=Wiener />{{rp|115}}<ref name=Borch>{{cite journal|last1=Borch|first1=Fred L., III|title='The Largest Murder Trial in the History of the United States': The Houston Riots Court-Martial of 1917|journal=The Army Lawyer|date=2011|issue=February 2011|pages=1\u20133|url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/frd/Military_Law/pdf/02-2011.pdf#page=5}}</ref>{{rp|2\u20133}} Those boards, though they had advisory power only, were the Army's first appellate courts.<ref name=Borch/>{{rp|3}})\n\nWhile waiting for the JAG review to occur, Ruckman approved a third [[court-martial]], the \"Tillman\" case, of forty more soldiers. On March 26, 1918, twenty-three of those forty soldiers were found guilty. Eleven of the twenty-three were sentenced to death and the remaining twelve to life in prison. On May 2, Ruckman approved the sentences.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Wilson's clemency and commentary==\n[[File:Prisoner at Leavenworth Federal Penitentiary. LeRoy Pinkett - NARA - 292117.tif|thumb|Private LeRoy Pickett, convicted of murder, mutiny, and assault with intent to murder. Sentenced to death but received clemency. He was released from prison in 1935.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4LMrDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46&dq=LeRoy+Pinkett#v=onepage|title=Camp Logan|first=Priscilla T.|last=Graham|date=13 April 2019|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=9781387021086|via=Google Books}}</ref>]]\nOn August 31, 1918, [[Woodrow Wilson|President Wilson]] granted clemency to ten soldiers by commuting their death sentences to life in prison.<ref name=\"morris\"/> Wilson issued a rare public statement in order that the basis of his action might be \"a matter of record.\"<ref name=\"wilson\">{{Cite news|issn=0362-4331|page=10|title=President Saves Rioters; Commutes Sentences of Half a Score of Negro Soldiers Convicted of Murder.|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2013-03-02|date=September 5, 1918|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60610FA3F5D147A93C7A91782D85F4C8185F9}}</ref>\n\nThe President's statement began by recounting the events that led to the deaths of \"innocent bystanders\" who were \"peaceable disposed civilians of the City of Houston.\"<ref name=\"morris\">{{cite book|last=Morris|first=Lawrence J.|title=Military Justice: A Guide to the Issues|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SERsEA9uHtUC&pg=PP1|year=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-275-99366-5}}</ref> He noted the investigations that followed were \"very searching and thorough.\" In each of the three proceedings, the court was \"properly constituted\" and composed of \"officers of experience and sobriety of judgment.\" Wilson also noted \"extraordinary precautions\" were taken to \"insure the fairness of the trials\" and, in each instance, the rights of the defendants were \"surrounded at every point\" by the \"safeguards\" of \"a humane administration of the law.\" As a result, there were \"no legal errors\" which had \"prejudiced the rights of the accused.\"<ref name=\"wilson\"/>\n \nWilson stated that he affirmed the death sentences of six soldiers because there was \"plain evidence\" that they \"deliberately\" engaged in \"shocking brutality.\"<ref name=\"wilson\"/> On the other hand, he commuted the remaining sentences because he believed the \"lesson\" of the lawless riot had already been \"adequately pointed.\" He desired the \"splendid loyalty\" of African American soldiers be recognized and expressed the hope that clemency would inspire them \"to further zeal and service to the country.\"<ref name=\"wilson\"/>\n\nMost importantly, from General Ruckman's standpoint, Wilson (a former law professor) wrote the actions taken by the former Commander of the Southern Department were \"legal and justified by the record.\" Indeed, the President agreed that \"a stern redress\" of the rioters' \"wrongs\" was the \"surest protection of society against their further recurrence\".<ref name=\"morris\"/> As historian Calvin C. Smith noted in 1991, there was no proof of a \"conspiracy\", and many of the sentenced were not conclusively identified in the dark and rainy night as having even participated in the riot.<ref name=\"smith1991\">{{Cite journal|volume= 13|pages=85\u201395|last=Smith|first=C. Calvin|title=The Houston Riot of 1917, Revisited|journal=Houston Review|accessdate=2013-03-02|year=1991|url=http://www.studythepast.com/4333_spring12/materials/houstonriot1917_houstonreview.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Smith\">{{Cite journal|volume= 10|issue=1|pages=3\u201312|last=Smith|first=C. Calvin|title=The Houston Riot of 1917, Revisited|journal=Griot|year=1991}}</ref> On September 29, 1918, five more soldiers met their deaths at daybreak. One week later, the sixth was marched to the gallows.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Camp Logan today==\n[[File:001 camp logan map.jpg|thumb|Map \u2013 Camp Logan (circa, 1917)]]\nThe area where Camp Logan was located is now called [[Memorial Park, Houston|Memorial Park]]. It is bordered by highways I-10 and I-610.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n*The hanging of the first 13 soldiers is mentioned in part 4 of the 1979 television miniseries ''[[Roots: The Next Generations]]''.\n*[[KHOU]], a CBS affiliated TV station located in Houston produced a documentary of the riot in 2006 entitled ''Mutiny on the Bayou: The Camp Logan Story''.<ref>{{cite book|publisher=KHOU TV|title=Mutiny on the Bayou|oclc = 64667563}}</ref>\n*''[[The 24th]]'', a movie about the riot, was filmed partly in the Brooklyn-South Square section of [[Salisbury, North Carolina]] in June 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.salisburypost.com/2019/06/27/brooklyn-south-square-neighborhood-tunes-in-as-the-24th-continues-filming/|title=Brooklyn-South Square tunes in as 'The 24th' continues filming|last=Moomey|first=Liz|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n*''Fire and Movement'' is a newly commissioned public performance by interdisciplinary Chicago-based artist Jefferson Pinder in 2019. The uprising saw African American soldiers of the 3rd Battalion of the 24th United States Infantry revolt and attempt to march on the city police department after experiencing abuse from white citizens and the police in Jim Crow-era Houston. \u00a0On July 11, 2019, Pinder and a trained group of performers retraced the route taken by African American soldiers. This incident is one of Houston\u2019s most complicated and often-misrepresented historical events.\n*''[[The 24th]]'', a film by [[Kevin Willmott]] about events.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Law|Texas|World War I}}\n* [[1917 in the United States]]\n* [[History of the African-Americans in Houston]]\n* [[Turner W. Bell]] \u2013 famous black lawyer who defended some of the soldiers\n* [[Military history of African Americans]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Aulbach|first=Louis F.|title=Buffalo Bayou: An Echo of Houston's Wilderness Beginnings|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qqZGLwEACAAJ&pg=PP1|year=2011|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|isbn=978-1-4681-0199-7|chapter=The Tragic Violence Along Buffalo Bayou in 1917}}\n* {{cite news |last=Dewey |first=Andy |title=The Texas history that's not in the textbooks |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |date=August 23, 2016 |url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/local/gray-matters/article/The-Texas-history-that-students-don-t-learn-9173079.php?t=185d5ca689438d9cbb}}\n* James, Rawn Jr. ''[https://archive.org/details/doublevhowwarspr0000jame The Double V: How Wars, Protest, and Harry Truman Desegregated America's Military]''. New York: Bloomsbury Press, 2013. {{ISBN|978-1-60819-622-7}}.\n* {{cite journal |last=Haynes |first=Robert V. |date=April 1973 |title=The Houston Mutiny and Riot of 1917 |journal=[[Southwestern Historical Quarterly]] |volume=76 |issue=4 |pages=418\u2013439 |jstor=30238208}}\n*{{cite HOT |id=jch04 |title=Houston Riot of 1917 |first=Robert V. |last=Haynes |date=June 15, 2010}}\n* {{cite book|last=McEachin|first=James|authorlink=James McEachin|title=Farewell to the Mockingbirds: A Novel|url=https://archive.org/details/farewelltomockin00mcea|url-access=registration|year=1997|publisher=Rharl Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-9656661-9-0}} (Novelization of the riot.)\n* {{cite book|last=McGhee|first=Fred. L.|title=Two Texas Race Riots|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l1J6MAEACAAJ&pg=PP1|year=2012|publisher=Fidelitas Publishing|isbn=978-0-615-62879-0}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Smith |first=C. Calvin |date=1991 |url=https://houstonhistorymagazine.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/houston-riot-1917-revisited.pdf |title=The Houston Riot of 1917, Revisited |journal=The Houston Review |publisher=Houston Public Library |volume=13 |issue=2 |pages=85\u201395}}\n* {{cite news |last=Wisenberg |first=S.L. |title=The 1917 Houston riot. And the era of Black Lives Matter |work=Houston Chronicle |date=August 23, 2016 |url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/local/gray-matters/article/What-the-Camp-Logan-riot-means-in-the-era-of-9179496.php}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Commercial & Financial Chronicle ...: A Weekly Newspaper Representing the Industrial Interests of the United States|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LAo8AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA2337|volume=Volume 105, Part II|year=1918|publisher=William B. Dana Company|page=2337|chapter=Thirteen Negro Soldiers Hanged for Rioting in Houston, Texas}} List of 13 executed\n*{{cite news |title=Negro Soldiers Must Die |work=Woodville Republican |location=Woodville, Mississippi |date=January 12, 1918 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=999&dat=19180112&id=OmAlAAAAIBAJ&pg=3782,553912&hl=en}} List of five sentenced to be executed\n*{{cite web |url=http://cdm16035.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/landingpage/collection/p15568coll1 |title=Houston Mutiny and Riot Records|work=The Fred Parks Law Library |publisher=Houston College of Law}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120225060303/http://www.stcl.edu/library/1917riot/index.html Symposium: The Largest Murder Trial in American History:  Exploring the Houston Riot of 1917 and its Impact on Military Justice Today]\n\n{{Houston Police Department}}\n\n[[Category:African-American history in Houston]]\n[[Category:History of Houston]]\n[[Category:1917 in Texas]]\n[[Category:1917 riots]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1917]]\n[[Category:African-American riots in the United States]]\n[[Category:African-American history of the United States military]]\n[[Category:Events that led to courts-martial]]\n[[Category:Military discipline and World War I]]\n[[Category:Mutinies]]\n[[Category:Riots and civil disorder in Texas]]\n[[Category:United States home front during World War I]]\n[[Category:August 1917 events]]\n[[Category:1917 murders in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox civil conflict\n| image = [[File:Largest Murder Trial in the History of the United States. Scene during Court Martial of 64 members . . . - NARA - 533485.tif|300px]]\n| place = [[Houston, Texas]]\n| date = \n| caption = Court Martial of 64 members of the 24th Infantry. Trial started November 1, 1917, [[Fort Sam Houston]]\n| map_type = \n| map_caption = \n| map_size = \n| goals   = \n| side1= [[24th Infantry Regiment (United States)|Twenty-fourth United States Infantry Regiment]] soldiers\n| side2= [[Houston Police Department|Houston police]]\n| leadfigures1= Regiment commander\n| leadfigures2= [[General John Wilson Ruckman]];<br /> Sheriff John Tobin;<br /> [[Woodrow Wilson]] \n| casualties1= '''Deaths''': 20 (19 executed after court-martials and other proceedings; 1 suicide)<br />'''Injuries''': <br />'''Arrests''': 51+\n| casualties2= '''Deaths''': 16 (11 civilians and five policemen; 4 soldiers killed by friendly fire)<br />unknown number of wounded\n| casualties_label= Arrests, etc\n}}\nThe '''Camp Logan Mutiny''' (also called the '''Houston Riot of 1917''') was a reaction by 156 soldiers of the Third Battalion of the all-black [[24th Infantry Regiment (United States)|Twenty-fourth United States Infantry Regiment]] after members of the [[Houston Police Department]] harassed members of the local black community and the black soldiers who attempted to intervene were also violently accosted.  It took place over a single night, and resulted in the deaths of 11 civilians, five policemen, and four soldiers. The soldiers were tried at three [[courts-martial]] for [[mutiny]]. Nineteen were executed, and 41 were sentenced to life imprisonment.\n\nGregg Andrews, author of ''Thyra J. Edwards: Black Activist in the Global Freedom Struggle'', wrote that the event \"shook race relations in the city and created conditions that helped to spark a statewide surge of wartime racial activism\".<ref>Andrews, Gregg. ''Thyra J. Edwards: Black Activist in the Global Freedom Struggle''. [[University of Missouri Press]], 2011/06/14. {{ISBN|0826219128}}, 9780826219121. p. [https://archive.org/details/thyrajedwardsbla00andr/page/20 20].</ref>\n\n==Preliminary situation==\n[[File:003 Map of Buffalo Bayou area - Camp Logan Riots.jpg|thumb|left|Map of Buffalo Bayou area \u2013 Camp Logan Riots (circa 1917)]]\nShortly after the United States declared war on the [[Imperial Germany|German Empire]] in the spring of 1917, the War Department rushed to construct two new military installations in [[Harris County, Texas]] \u2014 [[Camp Logan]] and [[Ellington Field]].<ref name=\"eric.ed.gov\">{{Citation|last=Johnson|first=Thomas A.|title=A History of the Houston Police Department|accessdate=2013-03-02|year=1999|url=http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/detail?accno=ED446013}}</ref> On July 27, 1917, the Army ordered the Third Battalion of the Twenty-fourth United States Infantry Regiment to Houston to guard the Camp Logan construction site. The regiment traveled to Houston by train from their camp at [[Columbus, New Mexico]], accompanied by seven commissioned officers.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n== Precipitating causes==\nAlmost from the arrival of the Twenty-fourth Infantry in Houston, the presence of black soldiers in the segregated Texas city caused conflict.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\">{{cite court |litigants=United States vs. Sergeant William C. Nesbit, et al.|vol=vol 1|url=http://cdm16035.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p15568coll1/id/2058/rec/7 }}</ref>{{rp|10}} The [[Jim Crow laws]] had not been enforced when the Twenty-fourth was deployed in [[Columbus, New Mexico]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Negro Uprising Been Feared For Days, Says Chief|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=August 24, 1917|page=5}}</ref> but in Houston the soldiers encountered segregated street cars and white workers at Camp Logan who demanded separate tanks of drinking water. Soldiers from the Twenty-fourth were involved in a number of \"clashes\" with city police, several of which resulted in the soldiers receiving minor injuries.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|10}}\n\nAround noon August 23, 1917, Lee Sparks and Rufus Daniels, two [[Houston]] police officers, broke up a craps game on a street corner in Houston's predominantly-black San Felipe district by firing warning shots.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|12}} Sparks, searching for the fleeing suspects, entered the house of local resident Sara Travers.<ref name=\"HoustonMutiny\">{{cite journal|title=The Houston Mutiny of 1917|journal=Trotter Review|date=January 1, 2009|last=Christian|first=Garna L.|volume=18|issue=1|page=112|url=http://scholarworks.umb.edu/trotter_review/vol18/iss1/14}}</ref> He did not find the suspect but, after exchanging words with Travers, struck her and dragged her outside in her nightgown.<ref name=\"crisis.nov.1917\">{{Cite news|issn=0011-1422|volume=15|issue=1|pages=14\u201319|last=Greuning|first=Martha|title=Houston: An N.A.A.C.P. Investigation|work=[[The Crisis]]|date=November 1917|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O1oEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14}}</ref>\n\nAs Sparks and Daniels called in the arrest from an area patrol box, they were approached by Private Alonzo Edwards. Edwards offered to take custody of Travers, but was pistol-whipped repeatedly by Sparks and then arrested.<ref name=\"crisis.nov.1917\"/> Later that afternoon, Corporal Charles Baltimore approached Sparks and Daniels in the same neighborhood to inquire about the status of Edwards. Sparks struck Baltimore with his pistol and fired three shots at him as he fled into a nearby home. Sparks and Daniels pursued Baltimore, eventually finding him under a bed. They pulled him out, beat him, and placed him under arrest.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|10}}\n\nA rumor reached the camp of the Twenty-fourth that Baltimore had been shot and killed. The soldiers immediately began meeting in small groups to discuss plans to march on Houston and attack the police.<ref name=\"Tillman\">{{cite court|litigants=United States vs. Corporal Robert Tillman, et al., 24th Infantry|vol=vol 2|url=http://cdm16035.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p15568coll1/id/2068/rec/6}}</ref>{{rp|1390}} An officer from the Twenty-fourth retrieved the injured Baltimore from the police station, which seemed to calm the soldiers for the moment.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|126}}\n\n==The mutiny==\nThe officers of the Twenty-fourth continued to receive reports of impending trouble from the angry soldiers.<ref name=\"Washington\">{{cite court|litigants=Record of Trial by General Court Martial of Corporal John Washington, et al., 24th Infantry|vol=vol 1|pinpoint=p. 22|url=http://cdm16035.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p15568coll1/id/2055/rec/7}}</ref> Major K.S. Snow revoked all passes for the evening and ordered the guard to be increased, but later that evening stumbled upon a group of men stealing ammunition from one of the supply tents.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|39}} He ordered the men to assemble without arms and warned them that it was \"utterly foolish, foolhardy, for them to think of taking the law into their own hands.\"<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|40}} One of the men, who had smuggled his rifle into the formation, fired it and cried out that a mob was approaching the camp. At this point, order broke down completely and the soldiers mobbed the supply tents, grabbing rifles and ammunition.<ref name=\"Tillman\"/>{{rp|1292}}\n\nThe soldiers began firing indiscriminately into the surrounding buildings. After several minutes of shooting, Sergeant Vida Henry ordered the men in the area \u2013 about 150 \u2013 to fill their canteens, grab extra ammunition, and fall in to march on Houston.<ref name=\"Tillman\"/>{{rp|1295}} The group marched through neighborhoods on the outskirts of the city, firing at houses with outdoor lights. They fired on a car with two white occupants, but let a second car with black occupants leave unharmed.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|1214}} They marched nearly two and a half miles, all the way to the San Felipe district, before they encountered any police officers. Due to the disorganization of the police department, officers had only been sent out in small numbers<ref name=\"Haynes\"/>{{rp|141}} so the first police casualties occurred when a group of six officers stumbled upon the entire column of soldiers. Two policemen (including Rufus Daniels) were killed immediately, and one later died of wounds he had sustained.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|527}}\n\nThe soldiers stopped a car carrying two policemen, who were disarmed and shot. \nA few blocks later, an open-topped car carrying a man in an olive-drab uniform approached the column. Believing this to be the uniform of a Houston mounted policeman, the soldiers opened fire only to discover later that they had killed Captain Joseph W. Mattes of the Illinois National Guard.<ref name=\"Nesbit1\"/>{{rp|651}} The killing of a military officer drove home the seriousness of their actions and the pending consequences.<ref name=\"Haynes\"/>{{rp|162}}\nMattes' body was found mutilated to the point of being nearly unrecognizable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZHIaAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA577&lpg=PA577&dq=Captain+Joseph+W.+Mattes+of#v=onepage|title=The Chicago Daily News Almanac and Year-Book|date=13 April 2019|publisher=Chicago Daily News Company|via=Google Books}}</ref>\nMany soldiers began to desert the group, and Sergeant Henry led the remainder on a march to return to camp. Just outside the San Felipe district, Henry shook hands with the remaining soldiers and informed them that he planned to kill himself after they left.<ref name=\"Tillman\"/>{{rp|1322}} Henry's body was found in the area the next day, with a crushed skull and bayonet wound to the shoulder..<ref name=\"henryinquest\">{{Cite web|url=http://cdm16035.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15568coll1/id/2145/rec/2|title=Vida Henry Inquest|date=August 24, 1917}}</ref>\n\nBy the time the shooting had stopped, 17 people were dead (four police officers, nine civilians, and two soldiers).<ref name=\"listofdead\">{{cite news|title=17 Killed; 21 Are Injured in Wild Night|work=Houston Chronicle|date=August 24, 1917|page=1}}</ref> One soldier and a police officer later died from wounds sustained during the riot, and one soldier died from wounds sustained during his capture the next day. All of the wounds received by soldiers the night of the riot were the result of [[friendly fire|accidental shootings by fellow soldiers]].<ref name=\"Haynes\"/>{{rp|169}}\n\n==Immediate aftermath==\nThe next morning, Houston was placed under martial law.<ref name=\"martiallaw\">{{cite news|title=Martial Law Declared |work=[[Houston Post]]|date=August 24, 1917|page=1}}</ref> The remaining soldiers in the Twenty-fourth's camp were disarmed, and a house-to-house search discovered a number of soldiers hiding in the San Felipe district. Soldiers in local jails were turned over to the Army, and the Third Battalion was sent by rail back to New Mexico.<ref name=\"Trotter, Joe W 2001\">{{Cite book|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Company|last=Trotter|first=Joe William|title=The African American Experience: From Reconstruction|location=Boston|year=2001}}</ref>\n\nIn the ensuing [[court-martial]], almost two hundred witnesses testified over twenty-two days, and the transcripts of the testimony covered more than two thousand pages. Author Robert V. Haynes suggests that [[General John Wilson Ruckman]] was \"especially anxious for the courts-martial to begin\".<ref name=\"Haynes\">{{cite book|last=Haynes|first=Robert V.|title=A Night of Violence: The Houston Riot of 1917|url=https://archive.org/details/nightofviolencet00hayn|url-access=registration|year=1976|publisher=Louisiana State University Press|isbn=978-0-8071-0172-8}}</ref>{{rp|251}}\n\nRuckman had preferred the proceedings take place in [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]], but eventually agreed to allow them to remain in [[San Antonio]]. Haynes posits the decision was made to accommodate the witnesses who lived in Houston, plus \"the countless spectators\" who wanted to follow the proceedings (p.&nbsp;254).<ref name=\"Haynes\"/> Ruckman \"urged\" the War Department to select a \"prestigious court\".<ref name=\"Haynes\"/>{{rp|255}} Three brigadier generals were chosen, along with seven full colonels and three lieutenant colonels. Eight members of the court were [[West Point]] graduates. The court contained a geographic balance between northerners, southerners and westerners.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n[[File:002 Map 24th infantry camp; Houston, Texas, showing bullet holes in vicinity.jpg|thumb|left|Map 24th infantry camp; Houston, Texas, showing bullet holes in vicinity (circa 1917)]]\nThe Departmental Judge Advocate General, Colonel George Dunn, reviewed the record of the first court martial (known as \"the Nesbit Case.\") and approved the sentences. He forwarded the documents materials to Gen. Ruckman on December 3. Six days later, thirteen of the prisoners (including Corporal Baltimore) were told that they would be hanged for murder, but they were not informed of the time or place.<ref name=\"Haynes\"/>{{rp|3}} The court recommended clemency for a Private Hudson, but General Ruckman declined to grant it.\n\nThough 169 witnesses testified for the prosecution during the 22-day court-martial, many could not identify the defendants because the riots unfolded at night during heavy rain. Historians have also questioned the veracity of witness testimony, noting that the soldiers who testified as participants were granted immunity or promised leniency.<ref name=\"WaPo_082417\">{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Deneen L.|title=Relatives seek justice for the mass hanging of black soldiers after the bloody 1917 Houston riots|url=https://www.stripes.com/relatives-seek-justice-for-the-mass-hanging-of-black-soldiers-after-the-bloody-1917-houston-riots-1.484277|accessdate=February 12, 2018|agency=[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=August 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"smith1991\"/>\n\n==The first hanging==\nThe condemned soldiers (one sergeant, four corporals, and eight privates) were transferred to a barracks on December 10. That evening, motor trucks carried new lumber for scaffolds to some bathhouses built for the soldiers at Camp Travis near a swimming pool in the [[Salado Creek]]. The designated place of execution was several hundred yards away. Army engineers completed their work by the light of bonfires. The thirteen condemned men were awakened at five in the morning and brought to the gallows. They were hanged simultaneously, at 7:17am, one minute before sunrise. The scaffolds were disassembled and every piece returned to [[Fort Sam Houston]]. The ''[[New York Times]]'', commenting on the clean-up operations, observed the place of execution and place of burial were \"indistinguishable.\" Only army officers and County Sheriff John Tobin had been allowed to witness the execution.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nGen. Ruckman told reporters he had personally approved the death sentences and said that forty-one soldiers had been given life sentences and four received sentences of two and a half years or less. He said he was the one who chose the time and place for the executions.<ref name=\"Haynes\"/>{{rp|7}} Military jurist [[Frederick Bernays Wiener]] has observed that Ruckman's approval and execution of the death sentences were \"entirely legal\" and \"in complete conformity\" with the 1916 Articles of War.<ref name=Wiener/>{{rp|122}}\n\n==Second and third courts martial==\nA second court-martial, the \"Washington\" case, began six days later. Fifteen men of the Lower A Division were tried and five were sentenced to death. On January 2, 1918, Ruckman approved the sentences in a public statement. But a new rule, General Orders 167 (December 29, 1917), prohibited the execution of any death sentence until the [[Judge Advocate General]] (JAG) could review the sentence(s).<ref name=Wiener>{{cite journal|last1=Wiener|first1=Frederick Bernays|title=The Seamy Side of the World War I Court-Martial Controversy|journal=Military Law Review|date=1989|volume=123|pages=109\u201328|accessdate=December 11, 2015|url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/frd/Military_Law/Military_Law_Review/pdf-files/27607D~1.pdf#page=113}}</ref>{{rp|115}} (The JAG Boards of Review tasked with reviewing death sentences were created by a subsequent rule, General Orders 7 (January 7, 1918).<ref name=Wiener />{{rp|115}}<ref name=Borch>{{cite journal|last1=Borch|first1=Fred L., III|title='The Largest Murder Trial in the History of the United States': The Houston Riots Court-Martial of 1917|journal=The Army Lawyer|date=2011|issue=February 2011|pages=1\u20133|url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/frd/Military_Law/pdf/02-2011.pdf#page=5}}</ref>{{rp|2\u20133}} Those boards, though they had advisory power only, were the Army's first appellate courts.<ref name=Borch/>{{rp|3}})\n\nWhile waiting for the JAG review to occur, Ruckman approved a third [[court-martial]], the \"Tillman\" case, of forty more soldiers. On March 26, 1918, twenty-three of those forty soldiers were found guilty. Eleven of the twenty-three were sentenced to death and the remaining twelve to life in prison. On May 2, Ruckman approved the sentences.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Wilson's clemency and commentary==\n[[File:Prisoner at Leavenworth Federal Penitentiary. LeRoy Pinkett - NARA - 292117.tif|thumb|Private LeRoy Pickett, convicted of murder, mutiny, and assault with intent to murder. Sentenced to death but received clemency. He was released from prison in 1935.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4LMrDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46&dq=LeRoy+Pinkett#v=onepage|title=Camp Logan|first=Priscilla T.|last=Graham|date=13 April 2019|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=9781387021086|via=Google Books}}</ref>]]\nOn August 31, 1918, [[Woodrow Wilson|President Wilson]] granted clemency to ten soldiers by commuting their death sentences to life in prison.<ref name=\"morris\"/> Wilson issued a rare public statement in order that the basis of his action might be \"a matter of record.\"<ref name=\"wilson\">{{Cite news|issn=0362-4331|page=10|title=President Saves Rioters; Commutes Sentences of Half a Score of Negro Soldiers Convicted of Murder.|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2013-03-02|date=September 5, 1918|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60610FA3F5D147A93C7A91782D85F4C8185F9}}</ref>\n\nThe President's statement began by recounting the events that led to the deaths of \"innocent bystanders\" who were \"peaceable disposed civilians of the City of Houston.\"<ref name=\"morris\">{{cite book|last=Morris|first=Lawrence J.|title=Military Justice: A Guide to the Issues|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SERsEA9uHtUC&pg=PP1|year=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-275-99366-5}}</ref> He noted the investigations that followed were \"very searching and thorough.\" In each of the three proceedings, the court was \"properly constituted\" and composed of \"officers of experience and sobriety of judgment.\" Wilson also noted \"extraordinary precautions\" were taken to \"insure the fairness of the trials\" and, in each instance, the rights of the defendants were \"surrounded at every point\" by the \"safeguards\" of \"a humane administration of the law.\" As a result, there were \"no legal errors\" which had \"prejudiced the rights of the accused.\"<ref name=\"wilson\"/>\n \nWilson stated that he affirmed the death sentences of six soldiers because there was \"plain evidence\" that they \"deliberately\" engaged in \"shocking brutality.\"<ref name=\"wilson\"/> On the other hand, he commuted the remaining sentences because he believed the \"lesson\" of the lawless riot had already been \"adequately pointed.\" He desired the \"splendid loyalty\" of African American soldiers be recognized and expressed the hope that clemency would inspire them \"to further zeal and service to the country.\"<ref name=\"wilson\"/>\n\nMost importantly, from General Ruckman's standpoint, Wilson (a former law professor) wrote the actions taken by the former Commander of the Southern Department were \"legal and justified by the record.\" Indeed, the President agreed that \"a stern redress\" of the rioters' \"wrongs\" was the \"surest protection of society against their further recurrence\".<ref name=\"morris\"/> As historian Calvin C. Smith noted in 1991, there was no proof of a \"conspiracy\", and many of the sentenced were not conclusively identified in the dark and rainy night as having even participated in the riot.<ref name=\"smith1991\">{{Cite journal|volume= 13|pages=85\u201395|last=Smith|first=C. Calvin|title=The Houston Riot of 1917, Revisited|journal=Houston Review|accessdate=2013-03-02|year=1991|url=http://www.studythepast.com/4333_spring12/materials/houstonriot1917_houstonreview.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Smith\">{{Cite journal|volume= 10|issue=1|pages=3\u201312|last=Smith|first=C. Calvin|title=The Houston Riot of 1917, Revisited|journal=Griot|year=1991}}</ref> On September 29, 1918, five more soldiers met their deaths at daybreak. One week later, the sixth was marched to the gallows.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Camp Logan today==\n[[File:001 camp logan map.jpg|thumb|Map \u2013 Camp Logan (circa, 1917)]]\nThe area where Camp Logan was located is now called [[Memorial Park, Houston|Memorial Park]]. It is bordered by highways I-10 and I-610.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n*The hanging of the first 13 soldiers is mentioned in part 4 of the 1979 television miniseries ''[[Roots: The Next Generations]]''.\n*[[KHOU]], a CBS affiliated TV station located in Houston produced a documentary of the riot in 2006 entitled ''Mutiny on the Bayou: The Camp Logan Story''.<ref>{{cite book|publisher=KHOU TV|title=Mutiny on the Bayou|oclc = 64667563}}</ref>\n*''[[The 24th]]'', a movie about the riot, was filmed partly in the Brooklyn-South Square section of [[Salisbury, North Carolina]] in June 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.salisburypost.com/2019/06/27/brooklyn-south-square-neighborhood-tunes-in-as-the-24th-continues-filming/|title=Brooklyn-South Square tunes in as 'The 24th' continues filming|last=Moomey|first=Liz|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n*''Fire and Movement'' is a newly commissioned public performance by interdisciplinary Chicago-based artist Jefferson Pinder in 2019. The uprising saw African American soldiers of the 3rd Battalion of the 24th United States Infantry revolt and attempt to march on the city police department after experiencing abuse from white citizens and the police in Jim Crow-era Houston. \u00a0On July 11, 2019, Pinder and a trained group of performers retraced the route taken by African American soldiers. This incident is one of Houston\u2019s most complicated and often-misrepresented historical events.\n*''[[The 24th]]'', a film by [[Kevin Willmott]] about events.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Law|Texas|World War I}}\n* [[1917 in the United States]]\n* [[History of the African-Americans in Houston]]\n* [[Turner W. Bell]] \u2013 famous black lawyer who defended some of the soldiers\n* [[Military history of African Americans]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Aulbach|first=Louis F.|title=Buffalo Bayou: An Echo of Houston's Wilderness Beginnings|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qqZGLwEACAAJ&pg=PP1|year=2011|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|isbn=978-1-4681-0199-7|chapter=The Tragic Violence Along Buffalo Bayou in 1917}}\n* {{cite news |last=Dewey |first=Andy |title=The Texas history that's not in the textbooks |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |date=August 23, 2016 |url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/local/gray-matters/article/The-Texas-history-that-students-don-t-learn-9173079.php?t=185d5ca689438d9cbb}}\n* James, Rawn Jr. ''[https://archive.org/details/doublevhowwarspr0000jame The Double V: How Wars, Protest, and Harry Truman Desegregated America's Military]''. New York: Bloomsbury Press, 2013. {{ISBN|978-1-60819-622-7}}.\n* {{cite journal |last=Haynes |first=Robert V. |date=April 1973 |title=The Houston Mutiny and Riot of 1917 |journal=[[Southwestern Historical Quarterly]] |volume=76 |issue=4 |pages=418\u2013439 |jstor=30238208}}\n*{{cite HOT |id=jch04 |title=Houston Riot of 1917 |first=Robert V. |last=Haynes |date=June 15, 2010}}\n* {{cite book|last=McEachin|first=James|authorlink=James McEachin|title=Farewell to the Mockingbir